, and with Quellcrist.\n |LineColor = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 8\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 8\n |Title = Clash by Night\n |DirectedBy = Uta Briesewitz\n |WrittenBy = Brian Nelson\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n |ShortSummary = Faced with his sister's treachery, Kovacs gets Vernon's wife Ava released into a male sleeve to help him convince Laurens that his lawyer Oumou Prescott is the murderer. Ortega tries to determine the identity of the mystery woman who saved Kovacs.\n |LineColor = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 9\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 9\n |Title = Rage in Heaven\n |DirectedBy = Peter Hoar\n |WrittenBy = Russel Friend & Garrett Lerner\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n |ShortSummary = After Reileen issues a violent ultimatum, Kovacs and his associates plot to infiltrate her ship.\n |LineColor = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 10\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 10\n |Title = The Killers\n |DirectedBy = Peter Hoar\n |WrittenBy = Laeta Kalogridis & Nevin Densham\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n |ShortSummary = Everything is revealed as Kovacs confronts Reileen for the last time, and Lizzie faces the Bancrofts.\n |LineColor = 000000\n}}\n}}\n\n=== Season 2 (2020) ===\n{{Episode table |background=#470C14 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=21 |director=15 |writer=33 |airdate=21 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 11\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |Title = Phantom Lady\n |DirectedBy = [[Ciaran Donnelly (director)|Ciaran Donnelly]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Laeta Kalogridis]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = 30 years after the Bancroft case, a Meth locates Kovacs and offers him a job, a high-tech sleeve and the chance to see Quellcrist Falconer again.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 12\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |Title = Payment Deferred\n |DirectedBy = Ciaran Donnelly\n |WrittenBy = Sarah Nicole Jones\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = Colonel Carrera leads the murder investigation, Kovacs looks for Axley's bounty hunter and Poe's memory deteriorates.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 13\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |Title = Nightmare Alley\n |DirectedBy = [[M. J. Bassett]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Michael R. Perry]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = Carrera tortures Kovacs, struggling with ghosts from his past. Poe asks another AI for help. Trepp finds a clue about the man she is after.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 14\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |Title = Shadow of a Doubt\n |DirectedBy = M. J. Bassett\n |WrittenBy = Sang Kyu Kim\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = With Harlan's Day celebrations underway, Kovacs hatches an escape plan, Quell re-assembles pieces from her life and Poe handles a debt. \n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 15\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |Title = I Wake up Screaming\n |DirectedBy = Jeremy Webb\n |WrittenBy = Cortney Norris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = Carrera's secret weapon is assigned a deadly mission. Kovacs and Trepp sneak Quell out of the city. Poe takes a dangerous, virtual trip.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 16\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |Title = Bury Me Dead\n |DirectedBy = Jeremy Webb\n |WrittenBy = Adam Lash & Cori Uchida\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = Quell remembers of her past in Stronghold and leads the clone in an underground chamber filled with secrets. Governor Harlan shows her true colours.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 17\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |Title = Experiment Perilous\n |DirectedBy = [[Salli Richardson-Whitfield]]\n |WrittenBy = Nevin Densham\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = Quell's sleeve starts to break down. Poe and Ms Dig send her to VR, where Kovacs learns the truth about her killing sprees.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 18\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 8\n |Title = Broken Angels\n |DirectedBy = Salli Richardson-Whitfield\n |WrittenBy = [[Alison Schapker]] & Elizabeth Padden\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = With the whole planet in danger, Kovacs, Quell and the team search for Conrad Harlan in order to stop the destructive path of Angelfire.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n}}\n\n=== Film (2020) ===\n{{Episode table |background=#A42E14 |title=31 |director=15 |writer=33 |airdate=21 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |RTitle = ''Resleeved''\n |DirectedBy = Takeru Nakajima & Yoshiyuki Okuda\n |WrittenBy = [[Dai Sato]] & Tsukasa Kondo\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|19}}\n |ShortSummary = On the planet Latimer, Takeshi Kovacs must protect a tattooist while investigating the death of a yakuza boss alongside a no-nonsense CTAC.\n |LineColor = A42E14\n}}\n}}\n\n== Release ==\nThe series premiered on [[Netflix]] on February 2, 2018. The official trailer was released on January 11, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/tv-news-roundup-netflix-altered-carbon-1202661758/ |title=TV News Roundup: Netflix Releases Trailer for Cyberpunk Series 'Altered Carbon' (Watch) |last=Fernandez |first=Matt |date=January 12, 2018 |work=Variety|access-date=January 12, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> Season 2 was released on February 27, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paultassi/2020/02/27/netflixs-altered-carbon-is-live-now-with-a-much-shorter-season-2/#6925b4a47366 |title=Netflix\u2019s \u2018Altered Carbon\u2019 Is Live Now With A Much Shorter Season 2 |website=Forbes |first=Paul |last=Tassi |date=February 27, 2020 |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\nHuman-machine interface, gender identity, technology and society, cyberspace and objective reality, hyper-urbanization that passes up urban planning, artificial intelligence, paranoia.\n\n{{quotation|A key concept in Netflix's cyberpunk series ''Altered Carbon'' is the 'stack', an advanced hard drive installed on the brainstem on which a person can save a copy of their consciousness. The main effect of stack technology is a form of immortality, because a stack can be installed into another body if the original body dies. But there\u2019s another major implication only hinted at during the first season of ''Altered Carbon'': If you could choose your own body, would you go with the one you were born with? That's an especially important question for gender fluid or transgender people. The topic was only hinted at in the first season, but ''Altered Carbon'' creator Laeta Kalogridis told ''The Wrap'' it's something she would like to explore in greater detail.<ref name=\"Transgenderism\">{{cite web |url=https://thewrap.com/altered-carbon-transgender-stacks-lgbt-laeta-kalogridis/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' Creator on How Show Could Examine LGBTQ Issues in Season 2 |website=The Wrap |first=Jennifer |last=Maas |date=February 13, 2018 |access-date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical response ===\n==== Season 1 ====\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season holds an approval rating of 68% based on 95 reviews, and an average rating of 6.59/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Altered Carbon'' leans hard into its [[cyberpunk]] roots, serving up an ambitiously [[Pulp magazine|pulpy]] viewing experience that often overwhelms, but never bores.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Altered Carbon: Season 1 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/altered_carbon/s01 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the season has a weighted average score of 64 out of 100, based on 25 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/altered-carbon/season-1 |title=''Altered Carbon'': Season 1 |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDavid Griffin of [[IGN]] said the show \"gets almost everything right\" as a \"cyberpunk fantasyland.\" Griffin praised the visuals and the complexity of the plot, as well as the acting, such as Chris Conner's performance as the AI hotel manager Poe. He also wrote of the show's problems, such as the intricacies of the murder often got \"in the way of the show's momentum\" and the murder plot \"loses steam\" early on. He ultimately gave it a score of 8.8 out of 10, summarizing it as \"A visual titan with a less than stellar story.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/26/altered-carbon-season-1-review |title=''Altered Carbon'': Season 1 Review |last=Griffin |first=David |date=January 26, 2018 |publisher=[[IGN]] |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> Michael Rougeau of [[GameSpot]] made a point of calling it \"hardcore\" science fiction, as a \"noir sci-fi/[[Detective|gumshoe]] thriller bursting with the trappings of both genres, from murdered prostitutes and holographic billboard ads to AIs who flit between the real world and some convoluted [[cyberspace]].\" The review praised how deeply the show examined and explored the cortical stack, the central concept.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/netflixs-altered-carbon-contains-some-incredibly-h/1100-6456241/ |title=Netflix's ''Altered Carbon'' Contains Some Incredibly Hardcore Sci-Fi |last=Rougeau |first=Michael |date=January 26, 2018 |website=GameSpot |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> Catherine Pearson of ''[[Digital Spy]]'' said the visuals were magnificent and the themes fascinating, but that it had flaws; for example, the characters \"mumbling their way through long expository dialogue.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/review/a847897/altered-carbon-netflix-trailer-tv-series/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' spoiler-free review: Netflix's new series is gorgeous, but drags over 10 hours |last=Pearson |first=Catherine |date=January 22, 2018 |publisher=Digital Spy |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Vancouver Sun]]'' summarized that the reaction of professional critics was mixed, and that the critics' conclusion was that the \"murder mystery takes a back seat to the show's futuristic visuals.\"<ref name=VS>{{cite web |url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/television/hollywood-north-reviews-mixed-on-surrey-shot-altered-carbon |title=Hollywood North: Reviews mixed on Surrey-shot ''Altered Carbon'' |last=Brown |first=Scott |date=January 30, 2018 |website=[[Vancouver Sun]] |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' also summarized reviews, saying the consensus was that the visuals were spectacular, but the violence against women raised questions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/01/22/altered-carbon-netflix-reviews/ |title=Reviewers praise Netflix's ''Altered Carbon''{{'s}} spectacular visuals but question its violence |last=Holub |first=Christian |date=January 22, 2018 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref> Darren Franich of ''Entertainment Weekly'' gave it a \"B-\" grade and wrote that the \"show tackles race, gender, and class with all the subtlety of a blowtorch.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/01/22/altered-carbon-review/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' is an expensive sci-fi epic wrapped in a dull mystery: ''EW'' review |last=Franich |first=Darren |date=January 22, 2018 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' criticized other critics for speaking negatively of the show and called it \"terrific\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2018/02/03/the-critics-must-be-crazy-altered-carbon-is-a-fantastic-new-netflix-original/ |title=The Critics Must Be Crazy: ''Altered Carbon'' Is A Terrific New Netflix Original |last=Kain |first=Erik |date=February 3, 2018 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> and one of the best science fiction shows on television.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2018/02/05/netflixs-altered-carbon-is-the-best-hard-sci-fi-show-on-tv-this-side-of-westworld/#1b3dad78432c |title=Netflix's ''Altered Carbon'' Is The Best Hard Sci-Fi Show On TV This Side Of 'Westworld' |last=Tassi |first=Paul |date=February 5, 2018 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> Andrew Liptak of ''[[The Verge]]'' called it engrossing, but criticized the lack of focus on the relationships between the characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/22/16901344/altered-carbon-netflix-review-science-fiction |title=Immortality isn't all it's cracked up to be in ''Altered Carbon''{{'s}} violent cyberpunk future |last=Liptak |first=Andrew |date=February 2, 2018 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRobert Lloyd of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave it a mixed review, but particularly praised Kinnaman, even if the fight scenes were described as tedious in a way.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-altered-carbon-review-20180131-story.html |title=Netflix's ''Altered Carbon'' may be long and complicated, but it's good to have Joel Kinnaman back |last=Lloyd |first=Robert |date=February 2, 2018 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> Jen Chaney of ''[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]'' said the show was \"ambitious, convoluted, violent, derivative, and somehow simultaneously grimy and glossy,\" but ultimately gave it a negative review, saying \"the visual candy and philosophical subtext of ''Altered Carbon'' may wash over me, but none of it gets absorbed in any lasting way.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/02/altered-carbon-netflix-review.html |title=''Altered Carbon'' Is an Over-Stacked Cyberpunk Mess |last=Chaney |first=Jen |date=February 2, 2018 |publisher=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]] | access-date =February 2, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Radio Times]]'' wrote that the \"drama tries to find its groove by shifting erratically from noir detective drama to war epic to soap opera, ultimately failing to meet its own lofty ambitions: it's a thunderous haymaker that only manages to graze its target.\" The review noted that the show takes on too much, and that much of the story could have been left for a second season.<ref name=\"radiotimes\" /> Benjamin Lee at ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the series 3/5, praising the \"sheer ambitious scale of it all\" and \"it\u2019s an impressive step up from what we\u2019re usually offered.\" Lee compared it to the work of [[Paul Verhoeven]] only lacking the social commentary. He concludes \"it\u2019s refreshing to see a show so unashamed about its pulpiness. The spectacle might grow stale but for now, the flash is blinding.\"<ref name=\"theguardian18\" />\n\nMany critics focused on the show's violence. Gavia Baker-Whitelaw of ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' wrote that the show seemed to use \"the dystopian setting as an excuse for sexualized violence,\" and that the focus on dead, naked women's bodies \"was a massive distraction from the show's stronger points, like the well-choreographed fight scenes and Takeshi Kovacs' backstory.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/altered-carbon-review-netflix/ |title=The future is still sexist in Netflix's cyberpunk thriller ''Altered Carbon'' |last=Baker-Whitelaw |first=Gavia |date=January 21, 2018 |website=The Daily Dot |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Digital Spy]]'' defended the level of violence, arguing it accurately reflected the books, and was \"the point\" of the franchise, as \"without showing brutal, unremitting violence, ''Altered Carbon'' would fail to fully explore the dystopian reality it aims to present.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/altered-carbon/feature/a849125/altered-carbon-netflix-tv-series-violence/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' on Netflix is spectacularly violent \u2013 but is the bloodshed justified? |last=Pearson |first=Catherine |date=February 4, 2018 |website=[[Digital Spy]] |access-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> Kimberly Roots of [[TVLine]] also criticized the scenes of violence and nudity, and also said the story suffered from uneven pacing. However, she noted that the investigation part \"clicks along smartly,\" and that the fight sequences were \"sophisticated.\" She gave it a \"B-\" grade.<ref name=TVLINE>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2018/01/22/altered-carbon-review-netflix-joel-kinnaman-james-purefoy/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' Review: Sci-Fi Drama Is Visually Stunning, Unevenly Paced |last=Roots |first=Kimberly |date=January 22, 2018 |publisher=TVLine |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Season 2 ====\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the second season holds an approval rating of 85% based on 33 reviews, and an average rating of 7.16/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"While not quite there yet, a clearer sense of purpose and more defined characters help ''Altered Carbon'' sophomore season step closer to the brilliance of its source material.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Altered Carbon: Season 2 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/altered_carbon/s02 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> On Metacritic, the season has a weighted average score of 65 out of 100, based on 8 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/altered-carbon/season-2 |title=''Altered Carbon'': Season 2 |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2018\n| [[44th Saturn Awards]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best New Media Television Series|Best New Media Television Series]]\n| ''Altered Carbon''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/ |title='Black Panther,' 'Walking Dead' Rule Saturn Awards Nominations |last=McNary |first=Dave |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=March 15, 2018 |access-date=March 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6xwc1azco?url=http://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/ |archive-date=March 15, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[70th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Design|Outstanding Main Title Design]]\n| Lisa Bolan, Thomas McMahan, Yongsub Song, Byron Slaybaugh, Carlo Sa, Mert Kizilay\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.emmys.com/shows/altered-carbon |title=Altered Carbon |website=Emmys.com |access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Special Visual Effects|Outstanding Special Visual Effects]]\n| Everett Burrell, Tony Meagher, Joel Whist, Jorge Del Valle, Steve Moncur, Christine Lemon, Paul Jones, Antoine Moulineau, David Zaretti for \"Out of the Past\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2019\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[17th Visual Effects Society Awards]]\n| Outstanding Visual Effects in a Photoreal Episode\n| Everett Burrell, Tony Meagher, Steve Moncur, Christine Lemon, [[Joel Whist (visual effects supervisor)|Joel Whist]] for \"Out of the Past\"\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"style=\"text-align:center;\" |<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/artisans/awards/visual-effects-society-nominations-avengers-infinity-war-1203108109/|title=Avengers,\u2019 \u2018Lost in Space,\u2019 \u2018Ready Player One\u2019 Lead Visual Effects Society Nominations|work=Variety|first=Kristopher|last=Tapley|date=January 15, 2019|access-date=January 17, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| Outstanding Effects Simulations in an Episode, Commercial, or Real-Time Project\n| Philipp Kratzer, Daniel Fernandez, Xavier Lestourneaud, Andrea Rosa\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Compositing in a Photoreal Episode\n| Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Leroux, Reece Sanders, Stephen Bennett, Laraib Atta\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.netflix.com/title/80097140|''Altered Carbon''}} on [[Netflix]]\n* {{IMDb title|2261227}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes TV|altered_carbon}}\n* {{Metacritic television|altered-carbon}}\n* [https://screenrant.com/altered-carbon-terminology-guide-glossary/ ''Altered Carbon'' glossary at ScreenRant]\n\n{{Netflix original current series}}\n{{Richard K. Morgan}}\n\n[[Category:2010s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:2018 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Action web series]]\n[[Category:American science fiction television series]]\n[[Category:American science fiction web series]]\n[[Category:Cyberpunk television series]]\n[[Category:Dystopian television series]]\n[[Category:Dystopian web series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Neo-noir television series]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:Television programmes based on British novels]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 24th century]]\n[[Category:Thriller web series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Science-fiction television series}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name          = Altered Carbon\n| image              = Altered_Carbon_title.jpg\n| caption            = \n| genre              = [[Cyberpunk]]<br />[[Action fiction|Action-adventure]]<br />[[Drama (film and television)|Drama]]\n| based_on           = {{Based on|''[[Altered Carbon]]''|[[Richard K. Morgan]]}}\n| creator            = [[Laeta Kalogridis]]\n| starring           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Joel Kinnaman]]\n* [[James Purefoy]]\n* [[Martha Higareda]]\n* Chris Conner\n* [[Dichen Lachman]]\n* [[Ato Essandoh]]\n* [[Kristin Lehman]]\n* Trieu Tran\n* [[Ren\u00e9e Elise Goldsberry]]\n* [[Anthony Mackie]]\n* [[Lela Loren]]\n* [[Simone Missick]]\n* [[Dina Shihabi]]\n* [[Torben Liebrecht]]\n}}\n| composer           = [[Jeff Russo]]\n| country            = United States\n| network            = [[Netflix]]\n| picture_format     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[Ultra-high-definition television|Ultra HD]])\n* [[High dynamic range]]\n}}\n| audio_format      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Dolby Digital|5.1]]\n* [[Dolby Atmos]]\n}}\n| first_aired        = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n| last_aired         = present\n| company            = Virago Productions<br />[[James Vanderbilt|Mythology Entertainment]]<br />[[Phoenix Pictures]]<br />[[Skydance Media|Skydance Television]]\n| distributor        = [[Netflix#Subsidiaries|Netflix Streaming Services]]\n| executive_producer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Brian Nelson (screenwriter)|Brian Nelson]]\n* James Middleton\n* [[David Ellison]]\n* Dana Goldberg\n* Marcy Ross\n* [[Mike Medavoy]]\n* Arnold W. Messer\n* Bradley J. Fischer\n* [[James Vanderbilt]]\n* [[Nick Hurran]]\n* [[Russel Friend]]\n* [[Garrett Lerner]]\n* [[Steve Blackman (writer)|Steve Blackman]]\n* [[Alison Schapker]]\n* Laeta Kalogridis\n}}\n| producer           = [[John G. Lenic]]\n| runtime            = 46\u201366 minutes\n| num_seasons        = 2<!-- Only increment this when a new season is released. -->\n| num_episodes       = 18<!-- Only increment this when a new episode is released. -->\n| list_episodes      = #Episodes\n| website            = https://www.netflix.com/title/80097140\n| related            =\n}}\n\n'''''Altered Carbon''''' is an American [[cyberpunk]] web television series created by [[Laeta Kalogridis]] and based on the 2002 [[Altered Carbon|novel of the same title]] by English author [[Richard K. Morgan]].<ref name=\"HR17\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/netflix-orders-sci-fi-drama-857543 |title=Netflix orders sci-fi drama based on ''Altered Carbon'' |first=Elizabeth |last=Wagmeister |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 20, 2016 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> In a world where consciousness can be transferred to different bodies, [[Takeshi Kovacs]], a former soldier turned investigator, must solve a murder. The first season consists of ten episodes and premiered on [[Netflix]] on February 2, 2018.<ref name=\"photos\"/> On July 27, 2018, the series was renewed for a second season of eight episodes,<ref name=\"Season2\">{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/altered-carbon-season-2-netflix-anthony-mackie-1202887876/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' Renewed for Season 2 at Netflix With Anthony Mackie in Lead Role |last=Otterson |first=Joe |date=July 27, 2018 |work=Variety |access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref> which was released on February 27, 2020, with an [[anime]] film set before the first season released on March 19, 2020. The series received generally positive reviews.\n\n== Synopsis ==\n{{Main|Takeshi Kovacs}}\nThe series takes place over 360 years in the future,<ref name=MIRROR>{{cite web |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/altered-carbon-netflix-uk-release-11920273 |title=What is ''Altered Carbon'' on Netflix UK? Release date, plot and cast in the TV adaptation of the R-rated novel |last=Rowney |first=Jo-Anne |date=January 29, 2018 |website=[[Daily Mirror]] | access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref><ref name=CNET>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/netflix-debuts-trailer-for-cyberpunk-series-altered-carbon/ |title=Netflix debuts trailer for cyberpunk series ''Altered Carbon'' |last=Burton |first=Bonnie |date=January 12, 2018 |publisher=[[CNET]] | access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> with most episodes the first season set in the year 2384, in a futuristic metropolis known as Bay City.<ref name=\"radiotimes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2018-01-26/altered-carbon-netflix-review/ |title=Netflix's ''Altered Carbon'' is an ambitious mess |last=Allen |first=Ben |date=January 26, 2018 |website=[[Radio Times]] | access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> In the future, a person's memories and consciousness can be decanted in a disk-shaped device called a ''cortical stack'', which is implanted in the vertebrae at the back of the neck. These storage devices are of alien design and have been reverse engineered and mass-produced. Physical human or synthetic bodies are called \"sleeves\" and stacks can be transferred to new bodies after death, but a person can still be killed if their stack is destroyed. While this theoretically means anyone can live forever, only the wealthiest, known as \"Meths\" in reference to [[Methuselah]], have the means to do so through clones and remote storage of their consciousness in satellites.<ref name=\"radiotimes\" />\n\nTakeshi Kovacs, a political operative with mercenary skills, is the sole surviving soldier of the Envoys, a rebel group defeated in an uprising against the new world order.<ref name=INDJACK>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/altered-carbon-release-date-netflix-sci-fi-exclusive-trailer-first-look-a8090866.html |title=''Altered Carbon'': Exclusive first look at Netflix's new dystopian sci-fi series release date revealed |last=Shepherd |first=Jack |date=December 4, 2017 |website=[[The Independent]] | access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> In the first season, set 250 years after the Envoys are destroyed, his stack is pulled out of prison by 300-year-old Meth Laurens Bancroft, one of the wealthiest men in the settled worlds. Bancroft offers him the chance to solve a murder\u2014Bancroft's own\u2014to get a new shot at life. In the second season, set 30 years later, Kovacs, now in a new sleeve, continues to search for his lost love and Envoy leader Quellcrist Falconer.<ref name=\"theguardian18\">{{cite web |first=Benjamin |last=Lee |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/feb/01/altered-carbon-review-ambitious-netflix-sci-fi-is-flashy-flawed-and-fun |title=''Altered Carbon'' review \u2013 ambitious Netflix sci-fi is flashy, flawed and fun |website=[[The Guardian]] |date=February 1, 2018|access-date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Cast ==\n=== Main ===\n* [[Joel Kinnaman]] (season 1; flashbacks season 2),<ref name=\"kinnaman\"/> [[Anthony Mackie]] (season 2) and [[Ray Chase (voice actor)|Ray Chase]] (''Resleeved'')<ref name=\"S2Cast\"/> as [[Takeshi Kovacs|Takeshi \"Tak\" Kovacs]], the last Envoy, of an elite rebel group defeated 250 years prior to the start of the series. Kinnaman also portrays Elias Ryker, a police officer and Ortega's former lover, whose \"sleeve\" or body Kovacs inhabits during season 1. Mackie serves as a new host body for Kovacs in season 2.\n* [[James Purefoy]] as Laurens Bancroft (season 1), one of the wealthiest men alive, who lives in a skyscraper above the clouds and out of the reach of everyday people, ruthlessly powerful and wanting to exert control on those around him.<ref name=\"cast\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/08/altered-carbon-james-purefoy-cast-netflix-sci-fi-series-1201798410/ |title=''Altered Carbon'': James Purefoy, Martha Higareda & 2 others cast in Netflix series |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 4, 2016 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[Martha Higareda]] as Kristin Ortega (season 1; guest season 2), a smart and tough lieutenant in the Bay City Police Department who comes from a religious [[Mexican American]] family of cops.<ref name=\"cast\"/> \n* Chris Conner as Edgar Poe (seasons 1\u20132),<ref name=\"S2Cast\"/> an [[artificial intelligence]] (AI) that takes the likeness of [[Edgar Allan Poe]] and runs the hotel that serves as Kovacs' base of operations in Bay City.<ref name=\"poe\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/altered-carbon-chris-conner-ato-essandoh-cast-netflix-series-1201814011/ |title=''Altered Carbon'': Chris Conner & Ato Essandoh Cast In Netflix Series |first=Denise |last=Petski |website=Deadline.com |date=September 6, 2016 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"S2Cast\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/02/22/altered-carbon-season-2-cast/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' reveals new season 2 replacement cast |work=Entertainment Weekly |first=James |last=Hibberd |date=February 22, 2019 |access-date=February 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Dichen Lachman]] (season 1; guest season 2) and Elizabeth Maxwell (''Resleeved'') as Reileen Kawahara / Gina, Kovacs' sister, who shared his violent childhood, who joined the Envoys at the same time as him and apparently perished when the uprising was put down.<ref name=\"cast\"/> \n* [[Ato Essandoh]] as Vernon Elliot (season 1; guest season 2), a former Protectorate marine whose wife was imprisoned and daughter murdered.<ref name=\"poe\"/> \n* [[Kristin Lehman]] as Miriam Bancroft and Naomi Bancroft (season 1), Laurens' wife who has her own motivations, and their daughter who steals her mother's sleeve.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/altered-carbon-kristin-lehman-cast-netflix-sci-fi-series-1201855196/ |title=''Altered Carbon'': Kristin Lehman Cast In Netflix Sci-Fi Series |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |date=November 16, 2016 |newspaper=Deadline.com |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Lehman said she was \"really intrigued and challenged\" to play the character of Miriam, considering it different from her other work. Her background as a dancer helped her prepare for the role. Of the character's sexuality, \"She has commodified her sexuality and I was interested in exploring that side of the character.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/opinion/2018/02/02/altered-carbon-may-be-one-of-netflixs-most-expensive-shows-yet-but-is-it-any-good.html |title=Altered Carbon may be one of Netflix's most expensive shows yet, but is it any good? |last=Wong |first=Tony |website=[[Toronto Star]] |date=February 2, 2018 |access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref> \n* Trieu Tran as Mister Leung / Ghostwalker (season 1), a killer and \"[[Fixer (person)|fixer]]\" who kills and solves problems for a mysterious employer.<ref name=\"extra\">{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/09/altered-carbon-marlene-forte-trieu-tran-cast-netflix-series-1201818380/ |title=''Altered Carbon'': Marlene Forte & Trieu Tran Join Cast of Netflix Series |first=Denise |last=Petski |website=Deadline.com |date=September 12, 2016 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Ren\u00e9e Elise Goldsberry]] as Quellcrist \"Quell\" Falconer (n\u00e9e Nadia Makita) (seasons 1\u20132),<ref name=\"S2Cast\"/> a master strategist and scientist, the creator of Stacks and leader of the Envoys. She was seemingly killed when the rebellion was put down, additionally appearing in Kovacs' flashbacks and hallucinations.<ref>{{cite web |last= Swift |first= Andy |url=http://tvline.com/2016/07/13/renee-elise-goldsberry-leaving-hamilton-netflix-drama-altered-carbon/ |title=''Hamilton''{{'s}} Ren\u00e9e Elise Goldsberry boards Netflix drama ''Altered Carbon'' |date=July 13, 2016 |website=[[TVLine]] |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Lela Loren]] as Danica Harlan (season 2), the governor of Harlan's World and the daughter of its founder, Konrad Harlan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/altered-carbon-power-star-lela-loren-cast-season-2-netflix-sci-fi-drama-1202704957/|title=\u2018Altered Carbon\u2019: \u2018Power\u2019 Star Lela Loren Joins Season 2 Of Netflix\u2019s Sci-Fi Drama|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=White|first=Peter|date=August 27, 2019|access-date=August 27, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Simone Missick]] as Trepp, a [[bounty hunter]] (season 2)<ref name=\"S2Cast\"/>\n* [[Dina Shihabi]] as Dig 301 (season 2), an AI archaeologue who befriends Poe<ref name=\"S2Cast\"/>\n* [[Torben Liebrecht]] as Jaeger / Ivan Carrera (season 2),<ref name=\"S2Cast\"/> Kovacs' [[commanding officer]] in the CTAC Praetorian and surrogate father, later the leader of an elite fighting force called The Wedge operating on Harlan's World.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/altered-carbon-season-2-cast-character-guide/|title=Altered Carbon Season 2 Cast & Character Guide|date=February 27, 2020|website=ScreenRant|first=Hannah|last=Shaw-Williams|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> [[Daniel Bernhardt]] portrays the character's previous sleeve in a recurring capacity in seasons 1\u20132.\n\n=== Recurring===\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Byron Mann]] as O.G. Kovacs (season 1; flashbacks season 2) and Dimitri Kadmin (season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/pure-genius-alexis-krause-byron-mann-altered-carbon-1201852658/ |title=Byron Mann Joins ''Altered Carbon''; ''Pure Genius'' Adds Alexis Krause |first=Denise |last=Petski |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=November 10, 2016 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Tamara Taylor]] as Oumou Prescott (season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/02/altered-carbon-tamara-taylor-brittany-s-hall-ballers-1201911661/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' Casts Tamara Taylor; Brittany S. Hall Joins ''Ballers'' |first=Denise |last=Petski |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=February 14, 2017 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Marlene Forte]] as Alazne Ortega (season 1)<ref name=\"extra\"/>\n* [[Tahmoh Penikett]] as Dimitri (season 1)\n* [[Hiro Kanagawa]] as Captain Tanaka (season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/tv/2017/12/4/16733520/altered-carbon-trailer-netflix-joel-kinnaman |title=Netflix's ''Altered Carbon'' trailer paints a grotesque, violent dystopian future |first=Julia |last=Alexander |website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |date=December 4, 2017 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Hayley Law]] as Lizzie Elliot (seasons 1\u20132)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2018/02/189786/netflix-altered-carbon-sex-worker-lizzie-hayley-law |title=A Badass Black Girl Is The Best Thing About Netflix's Altered Carbon |last=Romero |first=Ariana |date=February 2, 2018 |website=Refinery29 |access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Will Yun Lee]] as Original Takeshi Kovacs / \"Kovacs Prime\" (seasons 1\u20132)<ref name=\"cast\"/>\n* [[Adam Busch]] as Mickey (season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/altered-carbon-casts-adam-busch-the-chi-jahking-guillory-1202048118/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' Casts Adam Busch; ''The Chi'' Adds Jahking Guillory |first=Denise |last=Petski |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=March 21, 2017 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Shanks]] as Horace Axley (season 2)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gateworld.net/news/2019/07/michael-shanks-to-appear-on-netflixs-altered-carbon/|title=Michael Shanks To Appear On Netflix\u2019s Altered Carbon|work=GateWorld|date=July 13, 2019|access-date=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Sen Mitsuji]] as Tanaseda Yukito (season 2)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/brave-new-world-series-cast-1203246955/|title=\u2018Brave New World\u2019 Series Adds Five to Cast, Including Kylie Bunbury, Joseph Morgan|last=Otterson|first=Joe|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=June 19, 2019|access-date=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Waleed Zuaiter]] as Samir Abboud (season 1)\n* [[James Saito]] (season 2) and [[Doug Stone (voice actor)|Doug Stone]] (''Resleeved'') as Tanaseda Hideki\n* [[Neal McDonough]] as Konrad Harlan (season 2)\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Development ==\n=== Production ===\n[[Netflix]] ordered the series in January 2016, fifteen years after [[Laeta Kalogridis]] [[Option (filmmaking)|optioned]] the novel with the intent of making a [[feature film]].<ref name=\"photos\">{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/12/04/altered-carbon-trailer-netflix/ |title=''Altered Carbon'': First teaser trailer for stunning Netflix sci-fi series |first=James |last=Hibberd |website=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=December 4, 2017 |access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> According to Kalogridis, the complex nature of the novel and its [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|R-rated]] material meant that it was a tough sell for studios before Netflix ordered the series.<ref name=\"photos\"/> The show was one of a number of dramas ordered in short order by Netflix, which had committed to spending $5 billion on original content.<ref name=\"HR17\" />\n\nKalogridis wrote the script and served as executive producer and [[showrunner]].<ref name=\"HR17\" /> [[Steve Blackman (writer)|Steve Blackman]] served as co-showrunner.<ref name=\"photos\"/> David Ellison, Dana Goldberg and Marcy Ross of [[Skydance Television]] also served as producers, as well as Brad Fischer and James Vanderbilt of Kalogridis' Mythology Entertainment.<ref name=\"HR17\" /> [[Miguel Sapochnik]] directed the [[Television pilot|pilot]] episode.<ref name=\"photos\"/><ref name=\"kinnaman\">{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/joel-kinnaman-altered-carbon-netflix-1201772819/|title=Joel Kinnaman to Star in Netflix Sci-Fi Series ''Altered Carbon''|first=Elizabeth|last=Wagmeister |website=Variety|date=May 12, 2016|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref> Morgan served as a consultant during the show's production.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/981607/Altered-Carbon-season-2-spoilers-series-Netflix-Richard-K-Morgan |title=Altered Carbon season 2 spoilers: What will happen in the new series? |last=Debnath |first=Neela |website=[[Daily Express]] |date=June 29, 2018 |access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe series was reportedly the most expensive Netflix production to date.<ref name=\"thestar\" /> The production costs were not disclosed but Kinnaman said it had \"bigger budget than the first three seasons of ''[[Game of Thrones]]''\".<ref name=\"theguardian18\" />\n\nAnn Foley served as costume designer. The production crew fitted about 2,000 costumers and custom made at least 500 pieces for the show, and emphasized \"grounded\" looks for future fashion but figured in specific details, such as a unique palette for Meth characters and subtle costume changes when different people are inhabiting the same sleeve.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/3/16965968/altered-carbon-netflix-ann-foley-costume-designer |title=How Altered Carbon's costume designer created the fashions for its futuristic world |website=The Verge |last=Liptak |first=Andrew |date=February 3, 2018 |access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|Filming|Locations}}\n[[File:Rosegarden ubc.jpg|thumb|[[University of British Columbia]] Rose Garden]]\nThe series is produced in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada.<ref name=\"thestar\">{{cite web |url= https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/television/opinion/2018/02/02/altered-carbon-may-be-one-of-netflixs-most-expensive-shows-yet-but-is-it-any-good.html |title=Altered Carbon may be one of Netflix's most expensive shows yet, but is it any good? |website=The Star |last=Wong |first=Tony |date=February 2, 2018 |access-date=July 27, 2018}}</ref>\nLaurens Bancroft's gardens was filmed in [[University of British Columbia|University of British Columbia Rose Garden]] and the lobby of the Marine Building served as Bancroft's home. The old [[Canada Post]] building was used as the location of The Wei Clinic, where Kovacs was tortured. Scenes with the Envoys were filmed on the [[Shannon Falls Provincial Park|Sea to Sky Gondola]] suspension bridge, in Squamish. Other Vancouver locations include the [[Vancouver Convention Centre#West Building|Convention Centre's West Building]], the visitor centre at [[VanDusen Botanical Garden]], the [[Museum of Anthropology at UBC|UBC Museum of Anthropology]] and [[The Qube (Vancouver)|The Qube]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/920831/Altered-Carbon-location-Netflix-filmed-set-Vancouver-Canada |title=Altered Carbon filming locations: Where was Altered Carbon filmed? Where is it set? |website=Express.co.uk |last=Debnath |first=Neela |date=February 21, 2018 |access-date=August 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Altered Carbon'' was renewed for a second season in July 2018. [[Anthony Mackie]] took over the lead role of Takeshi Kovacs, replacing the first season lead star Joel Kinnaman. Additionally, [[Alison Schapker]] joined the series as co-showrunner alongside Laeta Kalogridis.<ref name=\"Season2\"/> On May 23, 2019, it was announced that Schapker would be the primary showrunner for the series, replacing Laeta Kalogridis who is still credited as an executive producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/alison-schapker-showrunner-altered-carbon-overall-deal-skydance-tv-1202621566/|title=Alison Schapker Inks Overall Deal With Skydance TV, Named Sole Showrunner Of \u2018Altered Carbon\u2019|last2=Petski|first2=Denise|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 23, 2019|access-date=May 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Adaptation of the novels ===\n==== First season ====\nThe first season is based on Richard Morgan's 2002 novel ''Altered Carbon''. While most of the major plot points in the book are retained, the adaptation featured several major changes for characters and organizations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/books/919030/Altered-Carbon-book-show-different-changes-torture-scene-Richard-Morgan-sequel-book-two |title=Altered Carbon book vs show: How much did they change? 19 major differences EXPLAINED |website=Express.co.uk |first=Stefan |last=Kyriazis |date=February 16, 2018 |access-date=April 22, 2019}}</ref> In the novel, the Envoys are elite soldiers of the United Nations Protectorate based on Earth, quite the opposite of the freedom-fighting rebels of the show, originating from Harlan's World, where Kovacs was born.\n\nIn the book, Kovacs was imprisoned for his freelance work after leaving the Envoys, while in the show, Kovacs is a captured rebel. The character of Reileen Kawahara in the novel was merely Kovacs\u2019 ruthless underworld boss and had no blood relation with him, in contrast to their sibling relationship in the show. The Envoy who trained Kovacs in the book was Virginia Vidaura. The show's Vidaura is only a minor character. Instead, his trainer is given the name and backstory of Quellcrist Falconer, who in book three is the historical messiah-like figure.<ref>{{cite web |date= February 15, 2018 |last1= Radish |first1= Christina |title= 'Altered Carbon' Creator Laeta Kalogridis on Book Changes, Season 2 Plans, and 'Alita: Battle Angel' |url= http://collider.com/altered-carbon-season-2-laeta-kalogridis-interview/ |website= [[Collider.com]]}}</ref> Falconer's rebellion occurred not during Kovacs' training, as in the show, but long before Kovacs was born in the books.\n\nThe Hendrix is an AI character in the novel; it runs the hotel and takes the form of [[Jimi Hendrix]]. Hendrix's estate declined to license his image for the television series because of its violence. Instead, showrunner Kalogridis chose the likeness of [[Edgar Allan Poe]] and a [[Victorian era]] hotel for the replacement Poe character and said it would juxtapose well with the futuristic Bay City.<ref name=\"Hendrix\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/features/altered-carbon-laeta-kalogridis-adaptation-edgar-allan-poe-interview-1202830788/ |title=Why 'Altered Carbon' Boss Replaced Hendrix With Poe for Netflix Adaptation |last=Holloway |first=Daniel |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=June 7, 2018 |access-date=July 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Film ====\nOn November 7, 2018, Netflix announced a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] [[anime]] film serving to \u201cexpand the universe\u201d of the series and new elements of the story mythology was in active development. Titled ''Altered Carbon: Resleeved'', the feature uses character designs by manga artist Yasuo \u014ctagaki, is written by [[Dai Sat\u014d]] and Tsukasa Kondo, directed by Takeru Nakajima and Yoshiyuki Okada, produced by Anima, and features an original music score by Keigo Hoashi Kinuyiki Takahashi from Monaca. The film was released on March 19, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last=Ramos |first=Dino-Ray |title=Netflix Unveils \u2018Pacific Rim\u2019, \u2018Altered Carbon\u2019 & More In New Lineup Of Anime Originals |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/netflix-anime-pacific-rim-altered-carbon-cagaster-of-an-insect-cage-yasuke-trese-1202498191/ |website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=November 8, 2018 |date=November 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.netflix.com/title/81001991 |title=Altered Carbon: Resleeved |website=Netflix |access-date=December 30, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Rafael |first=Rafael Antonio |title=Altered Carbon: Resleeved Anime Reveals Director, Spring 2020 Debut |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2019-10-23/altered-carbon-resleeved-anime-reveals-director-spring-2020-debut/.152525 |website=Anime News Network |access-date=December 31, 2019 |date=November 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=The world of Altered Carbon is getting re-sleeved on March 19 with an all new anime that brings even more action, mystery, and cyberpunk goodness than ever before!pic.twitter.com/S1mYqsysKI |url=https://twitter.com/NXOnNetflix/status/1229918520747712515?s=20 |website=@NXOnNetflix |access-date=19 February 2020 |language=en |date=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Episodes ==\n{{Series overview\n| allreleased = y\n| released    = y\n| color1      = #000000\n| link1       = #Season 1 (2018)\n| episodes1   = 10\n| start1      = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n\n| color2      = #470C14\n| link2       = #Season 2 (2020)\n| episodes2   = 8\n| start2      = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n\n| color2S     = #A42E14\n| link2S      = #Film (2020)\n| linkT2S     = ''Resleeved''\n| start2S     = {{Start date|2020|3|19}}\n}}\n\n=== Season 1 (2018) ===\n{{Episode table |background=#000000 |overall=5 |season=5 |title=21 |director=15 |writer=33 |airdate=21 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |Title = Out of the Past\n |DirectedBy = [[Miguel Sapochnik]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Laeta Kalogridis]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n |ShortSummary = Convicted criminal Takeshi Kovacs awakens in a new body after two and a half centuries to help an extremely rich man, Laurens Bancroft, solve his own murder. Bancroft died just after his consciousness was uploaded and saved to a satellite, and the evidence suggests it was a suicide. Bancroft offers Kovacs a massive amount of wealth and Kovacs' freedom, but Kovacs declines. He is briefly interrogated by a police officer called Ortega, but makes it clear he doesn't want the case. Just before he checks into a gothic hotel run by an artificial intelligence, Kovacs is attacked by a high-class hitman called Dimitri. As Kovacs has been gone for two hundred and fifty years, he believes someone really did kill Bancroft and takes the case.\n |LineColor = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |Title = Fallen Angel\n |DirectedBy = [[Nick Hurran]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Steve Blackman (writer)|Steve Blackman]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n |ShortSummary = Lieutenant Kristin Ortega, already at odds with the Bancrofts, tracks Kovacs, who is investigating the long list of people who have threatened Laurens' life.\n |LineColor = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |Title = In a Lonely Place\n |DirectedBy = Nick Hurran\n |WrittenBy = [[Brian Nelson (screenwriter)|Brian Nelson]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2018|2|2}}\n |ShortSummary = Kovacs is invited to a party at the Bancroft mansion, where Laurens has assembled the many likely suspects in his murder.\n |LineColor = 000000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |