Color = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 14\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |Title = Shadow of a Doubt\n |DirectedBy = M. J. Bassett\n |WrittenBy = Sang Kyu Kim\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = With Harlan's Day celebrations underway, Kovacs hatches an escape plan, Quell re-assembles pieces from her life and Poe handles a debt. \n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 15\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |Title = I Wake up Screaming\n |DirectedBy = Jeremy Webb\n |WrittenBy = Cortney Norris\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = Carrera's secret weapon is assigned a deadly mission. Kovacs and Trepp sneak Quell out of the city. Poe takes a dangerous, virtual trip.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 16\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |Title = Bury Me Dead\n |DirectedBy = Jeremy Webb\n |WrittenBy = Adam Lash & Cori Uchida\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = Quell remembers of her past in Stronghold and leads the clone in an underground chamber filled with secrets. Governor Harlan shows her true colours.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 17\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |Title = Experiment Perilous\n |DirectedBy = [[Salli Richardson-Whitfield]]\n |WrittenBy = Nevin Densham\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = Quell's sleeve starts to break down. Poe and Ms Dig send her to VR, where Kovacs learns the truth about her killing sprees.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 18\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 8\n |Title = Broken Angels\n |DirectedBy = Salli Richardson-Whitfield\n |WrittenBy = [[Alison Schapker]] & Elizabeth Padden\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|27}}\n |ShortSummary = With the whole planet in danger, Kovacs, Quell and the team search for Conrad Harlan in order to stop the destructive path of Angelfire.\n |LineColor = 470C14\n}}\n}}\n\n=== Film (2020) ===\n{{Episode table |background=#A42E14 |title=31 |director=15 |writer=33 |airdate=21 |released=y |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |RTitle = ''Resleeved''\n |DirectedBy = Takeru Nakajima & Yoshiyuki Okuda\n |WrittenBy = [[Dai Sato]] & Tsukasa Kondo\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|3|19}}\n |ShortSummary = On the planet Latimer, Takeshi Kovacs must protect a tattooist while investigating the death of a yakuza boss alongside a no-nonsense CTAC.\n |LineColor = A42E14\n}}\n}}\n\n== Release ==\nThe series premiered on [[Netflix]] on February 2, 2018. The official trailer was released on January 11, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/tv-news-roundup-netflix-altered-carbon-1202661758/ |title=TV News Roundup: Netflix Releases Trailer for Cyberpunk Series 'Altered Carbon' (Watch) |last=Fernandez |first=Matt |date=January 12, 2018 |work=Variety|access-date=January 12, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> Season 2 was released on February 27, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paultassi/2020/02/27/netflixs-altered-carbon-is-live-now-with-a-much-shorter-season-2/#6925b4a47366 |title=Netflix\u2019s \u2018Altered Carbon\u2019 Is Live Now With A Much Shorter Season 2 |website=Forbes |first=Paul |last=Tassi |date=February 27, 2020 |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Themes ==\nHuman-machine interface, gender identity, technology and society, cyberspace and objective reality, hyper-urbanization that passes up urban planning, artificial intelligence, paranoia.\n\n{{quotation|A key concept in Netflix's cyberpunk series ''Altered Carbon'' is the 'stack', an advanced hard drive installed on the brainstem on which a person can save a copy of their consciousness. The main effect of stack technology is a form of immortality, because a stack can be installed into another body if the original body dies. But there\u2019s another major implication only hinted at during the first season of ''Altered Carbon'': If you could choose your own body, would you go with the one you were born with? That's an especially important question for gender fluid or transgender people. The topic was only hinted at in the first season, but ''Altered Carbon'' creator Laeta Kalogridis told ''The Wrap'' it's something she would like to explore in greater detail.<ref name=\"Transgenderism\">{{cite web |url=https://thewrap.com/altered-carbon-transgender-stacks-lgbt-laeta-kalogridis/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' Creator on How Show Could Examine LGBTQ Issues in Season 2 |website=The Wrap |first=Jennifer |last=Maas |date=February 13, 2018 |access-date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>}}\n\n== Reception ==\n=== Critical response ===\n==== Season 1 ====\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season holds an approval rating of 68% based on 95 reviews, and an average rating of 6.59/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Altered Carbon'' leans hard into its [[cyberpunk]] roots, serving up an ambitiously [[Pulp magazine|pulpy]] viewing experience that often overwhelms, but never bores.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Altered Carbon: Season 1 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/altered_carbon/s01 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the season has a weighted average score of 64 out of 100, based on 25 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/altered-carbon/season-1 |title=''Altered Carbon'': Season 1 |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDavid Griffin of [[IGN]] said the show \"gets almost everything right\" as a \"cyberpunk fantasyland.\" Griffin praised the visuals and the complexity of the plot, as well as the acting, such as Chris Conner's performance as the AI hotel manager Poe. He also wrote of the show's problems, such as the intricacies of the murder often got \"in the way of the show's momentum\" and the murder plot \"loses steam\" early on. He ultimately gave it a score of 8.8 out of 10, summarizing it as \"A visual titan with a less than stellar story.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/01/26/altered-carbon-season-1-review |title=''Altered Carbon'': Season 1 Review |last=Griffin |first=David |date=January 26, 2018 |publisher=[[IGN]] |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> Michael Rougeau of [[GameSpot]] made a point of calling it \"hardcore\" science fiction, as a \"noir sci-fi/[[Detective|gumshoe]] thriller bursting with the trappings of both genres, from murdered prostitutes and holographic billboard ads to AIs who flit between the real world and some convoluted [[cyberspace]].\" The review praised how deeply the show examined and explored the cortical stack, the central concept.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/netflixs-altered-carbon-contains-some-incredibly-h/1100-6456241/ |title=Netflix's ''Altered Carbon'' Contains Some Incredibly Hardcore Sci-Fi |last=Rougeau |first=Michael |date=January 26, 2018 |website=GameSpot |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> Catherine Pearson of ''[[Digital Spy]]'' said the visuals were magnificent and the themes fascinating, but that it had flaws; for example, the characters \"mumbling their way through long expository dialogue.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/review/a847897/altered-carbon-netflix-trailer-tv-series/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' spoiler-free review: Netflix's new series is gorgeous, but drags over 10 hours |last=Pearson |first=Catherine |date=January 22, 2018 |publisher=Digital Spy |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Vancouver Sun]]'' summarized that the reaction of professional critics was mixed, and that the critics' conclusion was that the \"murder mystery takes a back seat to the show's futuristic visuals.\"<ref name=VS>{{cite web |url=https://vancouversun.com/entertainment/television/hollywood-north-reviews-mixed-on-surrey-shot-altered-carbon |title=Hollywood North: Reviews mixed on Surrey-shot ''Altered Carbon'' |last=Brown |first=Scott |date=January 30, 2018 |website=[[Vancouver Sun]] |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' also summarized reviews, saying the consensus was that the visuals were spectacular, but the violence against women raised questions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/01/22/altered-carbon-netflix-reviews/ |title=Reviewers praise Netflix's ''Altered Carbon''{{'s}} spectacular visuals but question its violence |last=Holub |first=Christian |date=January 22, 2018 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref> Darren Franich of ''Entertainment Weekly'' gave it a \"B-\" grade and wrote that the \"show tackles race, gender, and class with all the subtlety of a blowtorch.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/01/22/altered-carbon-review/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' is an expensive sci-fi epic wrapped in a dull mystery: ''EW'' review |last=Franich |first=Darren |date=January 22, 2018 |website=Entertainment Weekly |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Forbes]]'' criticized other critics for speaking negatively of the show and called it \"terrific\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2018/02/03/the-critics-must-be-crazy-altered-carbon-is-a-fantastic-new-netflix-original/ |title=The Critics Must Be Crazy: ''Altered Carbon'' Is A Terrific New Netflix Original |last=Kain |first=Erik |date=February 3, 2018 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> and one of the best science fiction shows on television.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/insertcoin/2018/02/05/netflixs-altered-carbon-is-the-best-hard-sci-fi-show-on-tv-this-side-of-westworld/#1b3dad78432c |title=Netflix's ''Altered Carbon'' Is The Best Hard Sci-Fi Show On TV This Side Of 'Westworld' |last=Tassi |first=Paul |date=February 5, 2018 |website=[[Forbes]] |access-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> Andrew Liptak of ''[[The Verge]]'' called it engrossing, but criticized the lack of focus on the relationships between the characters.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/1/22/16901344/altered-carbon-netflix-review-science-fiction |title=Immortality isn't all it's cracked up to be in ''Altered Carbon''{{'s}} violent cyberpunk future |last=Liptak |first=Andrew |date=February 2, 2018 |website=The Verge |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nRobert Lloyd of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' gave it a mixed review, but particularly praised Kinnaman, even if the fight scenes were described as tedious in a way.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/la-et-st-altered-carbon-review-20180131-story.html |title=Netflix's ''Altered Carbon'' may be long and complicated, but it's good to have Joel Kinnaman back |last=Lloyd |first=Robert |date=February 2, 2018 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |access-date=February 2, 2018}}</ref> Jen Chaney of ''[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]'' said the show was \"ambitious, convoluted, violent, derivative, and somehow simultaneously grimy and glossy,\" but ultimately gave it a negative review, saying \"the visual candy and philosophical subtext of ''Altered Carbon'' may wash over me, but none of it gets absorbed in any lasting way.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/02/altered-carbon-netflix-review.html |title=''Altered Carbon'' Is an Over-Stacked Cyberpunk Mess |last=Chaney |first=Jen |date=February 2, 2018 |publisher=[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]] | access-date =February 2, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Radio Times]]'' wrote that the \"drama tries to find its groove by shifting erratically from noir detective drama to war epic to soap opera, ultimately failing to meet its own lofty ambitions: it's a thunderous haymaker that only manages to graze its target.\" The review noted that the show takes on too much, and that much of the story could have been left for a second season.<ref name=\"radiotimes\" /> Benjamin Lee at ''[[The Guardian]]'' gave the series 3/5, praising the \"sheer ambitious scale of it all\" and \"it\u2019s an impressive step up from what we\u2019re usually offered.\" Lee compared it to the work of [[Paul Verhoeven]] only lacking the social commentary. He concludes \"it\u2019s refreshing to see a show so unashamed about its pulpiness. The spectacle might grow stale but for now, the flash is blinding.\"<ref name=\"theguardian18\" />\n\nMany critics focused on the show's violence. Gavia Baker-Whitelaw of ''[[The Daily Dot]]'' wrote that the show seemed to use \"the dystopian setting as an excuse for sexualized violence,\" and that the focus on dead, naked women's bodies \"was a massive distraction from the show's stronger points, like the well-choreographed fight scenes and Takeshi Kovacs' backstory.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dailydot.com/parsec/altered-carbon-review-netflix/ |title=The future is still sexist in Netflix's cyberpunk thriller ''Altered Carbon'' |last=Baker-Whitelaw |first=Gavia |date=January 21, 2018 |website=The Daily Dot |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref> ''[[Digital Spy]]'' defended the level of violence, arguing it accurately reflected the books, and was \"the point\" of the franchise, as \"without showing brutal, unremitting violence, ''Altered Carbon'' would fail to fully explore the dystopian reality it aims to present.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/altered-carbon/feature/a849125/altered-carbon-netflix-tv-series-violence/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' on Netflix is spectacularly violent \u2013 but is the bloodshed justified? |last=Pearson |first=Catherine |date=February 4, 2018 |website=[[Digital Spy]] |access-date=February 9, 2018}}</ref> Kimberly Roots of [[TVLine]] also criticized the scenes of violence and nudity, and also said the story suffered from uneven pacing. However, she noted that the investigation part \"clicks along smartly,\" and that the fight sequences were \"sophisticated.\" She gave it a \"B-\" grade.<ref name=TVLINE>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2018/01/22/altered-carbon-review-netflix-joel-kinnaman-james-purefoy/ |title=''Altered Carbon'' Review: Sci-Fi Drama Is Visually Stunning, Unevenly Paced |last=Roots |first=Kimberly |date=January 22, 2018 |publisher=TVLine |access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Season 2 ====\nOn Rotten Tomatoes, the second season holds an approval rating of 85% based on 33 reviews, and an average rating of 7.16/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"While not quite there yet, a clearer sense of purpose and more defined characters help ''Altered Carbon'' sophomore season step closer to the brilliance of its source material.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Altered Carbon: Season 2 |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/altered_carbon/s02 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> On Metacritic, the season has a weighted average score of 65 out of 100, based on 8 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/altered-carbon/season-2 |title=''Altered Carbon'': Season 2 |website=[[Metacritic]] |access-date=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\"| Recipient\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2018\n| [[44th Saturn Awards]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best New Media Television Series|Best New Media Television Series]]\n| ''Altered Carbon''\n| {{nom}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/ |title='Black Panther,' 'Walking Dead' Rule Saturn Awards Nominations |last=McNary |first=Dave |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=March 15, 2018 |access-date=March 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6xwc1azco?url=http://variety.com/2018/film/news/saturn-awards-nominations-2018-black-panther-walking-dead-1202727752/