y-3795778-402.html|title=Biographie : Mariah Carey|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806011226/http://people.plurielles.fr/biographie/mariah-carey-3795778-402.html|archivedate=August 6, 2016|work=[[Plurielles]]|publisher=[[TF1 Group]]|accessdate=August 6, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>|nocert=yes}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of best-selling albums in Brazil]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n'''Works cited'''\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{Citation\n | last = Bronson\n | first = Fred\n | title = The Billboard Book of Number 1 Hits\n | publisher = Billboard Books\n | location = New York\n | year = 2003\n | isbn = 0-8230-7677-6\n | authorlink = Fred Bronson\n }}\n* {{Citation\n | last = Shapiro\n | first = Marc\n | title = Mariah Carey: The Unauthorized Biography\n | publisher = [[ECW Press]]\n | location = Toronto\n | year = 2001\n | isbn = 978-1-55022-444-3\n }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Mariah Carey}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rainbow (Mariah Carey Album)}}\n[[Category:Mariah Carey albums]]\n[[Category:1999 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Bryan-Michael Cox]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by David Foster]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Jermaine Dupri]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by DJ Clue?]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Rainbow\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Mariah Carey]]\n| cover      = Mariah Carey Rainbow.png\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1999|11|2|mf=y}}\n| recorded   = {{Start date|1999|5|29|mf=y}} \u2013 {{Start date|1999|10|21|mf=y}}\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      =\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=mtvasia/><ref name=rs/><ref name=usa/>\n| length     = 55:49\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| producer   = \n*Mariah Carey\n*[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]\n*James Wright\n*[[David Foster]]\n*[[Jermaine Dupri]]\n*[[Bryan-Michael Cox]]\n*[[DJ Clue]]\n*[[Steve Mac]]\n| prev_title = [[Number 1's (Mariah Carey album)|#1's]]\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[Glitter (soundtrack)|Glitter]]\n| next_year  = 2001\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Rainbow\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]]\n | single1date = September 21, 1999\n | single2     = [[Thank God I Found You]]\n | single2date = January 25, 2000\n | single3     = [[Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)]]\n | single3date = June 6, 2000\n | single4     = [[Crybaby (Mariah Carey song)|Crybaby]]\n | single4date = July 18, 2000\n | single5     = [[Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)#Mariah Carey version|Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)]]\n | single5date = August 8, 2000\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Rainbow''''' is the seventh studio album by American singer and songwriter [[Mariah Carey]]. It was released on November 2, 1999, by [[Columbia Records]]. The album followed the same pattern as Carey's previous two albums, ''[[Daydream (Mariah Carey album)|Daydream]]'' (1995) and ''[[Butterfly (Mariah Carey album)|Butterfly]]'' (1997), in which she began her transition into the [[Urban music|urban]] market. ''Rainbow'' contains a mix of [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]-influenced [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] jams, as well as a variety of slow ballads. On the album, Carey worked with [[David Foster]] and [[Diane Warren]], who, as well as [[Jimmy Jam & Terry Lewis]], replaced [[Walter Afanasieff]], the main balladeer Carey worked with throughout the 90s. As a result of her separation from her husband, [[Tommy Mottola]], Carey had more control over the musical style of this album, so she collaborated with several artists such as [[Jay-Z]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], and [[Snoop Dogg]], as well as [[Missy Elliott]], [[Joe (singer)|Joe]], [[Da Brat]], [[Master P]], [[98 Degrees|98\u00b0]], and [[Mystikal]].\n\nOn Carey's previous album, ''Butterfly'', she began incorporating several other genres, including R&B and hip hop, into her musical repertoire. In order to further push her musical horizons, Carey featured Jay-Z on the album's lead single, the first time in her career that another artist was featured on one of her lead singles. Carey wrote ballads that were closer to R&B than [[Pop music|pop]] for this album, and worked with Snoop Dogg and Usher on songs such as \"Crybaby\" and \"How Much,\" both of which featured strong R&B beats and grooves. Several of the ballads that Carey wrote during this period, including \"[[Thank God I Found You]]\" (written with [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Terry Lewis]]) and \"After Tonight\" (written with Diane Warren), mirrored sentiments she experienced in her personal life.\n\nFive singles were released from the album, two of which became number-one hits on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] chart, making ''Rainbow'' her seventh-consecutive studio album to produce a number-one song. The album's lead single, \"[[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]]\" featuring Jay-Z, became Carey's fourteenth number-one hit on the Hot 100, and topped the charts in Canada and New Zealand. \"[[Thank God I Found You]],\" featuring [[Joe (singer)|Joe]] and [[98 Degrees]], also topped the Hot 100, but achieved moderate international charting. The next two singles, \"[[Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)]] and \"[[Crybaby (Mariah Carey song)|Crybaby]]\" featuring Snoop Dogg, were released as a [[double A-side]]. The songs were at the center of a public feud in between Carey and Sony due to Sony's alleged weak promotion of the singles. Carey's cover of [[Phil Collins]]' \"[[Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)]]\" with [[Westlife]] peaked at number one in Ireland, Scotland and the United Kingdom.\n\n''Rainbow'' was well received by critics, who generally praised Carey's embrace of R&B and hip hop in her music. The album debuted at number two on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard 200|200]], with first week sales of 323,000. It was her first album in years to not reach number one. However, within a month, ''Rainbow'' was certified triple-[[RIAA certifications|Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting shipments of three million copies within the United States. Internationally, the album debuted atop the charts in France, and within the top five in Australia, Austria, Belgium, the Netherlands, Germany, Japan, and Switzerland. The album has sold an estimated eight million copies worldwide.\n\n==Background==\nSince her debut in 1990, Carey's career was heavily calculated and controlled by her husband and head of her label [[Sony Music Entertainment]], [[Tommy Mottola]].<ref name=\"shapiro2\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=91\u201392}}</ref> For years, Carey's albums had consisted of slow and meaningful ballads, devoid of any guest appearances or [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]-influenced melodies. In January 1995, as she recorded ''[[Daydream (Mariah Carey album)|Daydream]]'', Carey began taking more control over her musical style and genre influences.<ref name=\"shapiro2\"/> She enlisted the production skills and [[Rapping|rap]] styles of [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]], who was featured on the remix of her song \"[[Fantasy (Mariah Carey song)|Fantasy]].\" While Mottola was hesitant at first, Carey's persistence paid off<ref name=\"shapiro2\"/> when the song became an international chart topper, with critics calling the collaboration one of the pioneering songs of [[Pop music|pop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] musical collaborations.<ref name=\"shapiro3\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=93}}</ref>\n\nDuring the recording and production of Carey's ''[[Butterfly (Mariah Carey album)|Butterfly]]'' in 1997, she and Mottola separated, giving Carey an extended amount of control over the unfinished album.<ref name=\"shapiro3\"/> Following their separation, Carey began working with younger hip hop and R&B producers and songwriters, aside from her usual work with balladeers [[Walter Afanasieff]] and [[Kenneth Edmonds]].<ref name=\"shapiro4\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=94}}</ref> While the album incorporated several different genres and components that were not present in Carey's previous releases, ''Butterfly'' also included a balance of her classic ballads and newer R&B-infused jams.<ref name=\"shapiro4\"/> While Sony accepted Carey's new collaborations with writers and producers such as [[P. Diddy]] and [[Bone Thugs-n-Harmony]], they continued to focus their promotion on the ballads. After \"[[Honey (Mariah Carey song)|Honey]],\" the debut single from ''Butterfly'', was released in August 1997, Sony halted the release of the succeeding R&B-influenced jams, and released the ballad \"[[My All]]\" as the second worldwide single. ''Rainbow'' followed in its predecessors' footsteps, featuring even more hip hop and R&B.<ref name=\"shapiro4\"/>\n\n==Writing and recording==\nDuring the spring of 1999, Carey began working on the final album of her record contract with Sony, her ex-husband's label.<ref name=\"shapiro5\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=121}}</ref> Carey's lover at the time, [[Luis Miguel]], was in the midst of a European tour. In order to spend more time with him, she opted to record the album on the secluded island of [[Capri]], Italy, figuring the seclusion would also help her complete the album sooner.<ref name=\"shapiro5\"/> During this time, Carey's strained relationship with Sony affected her work with writing partner Afanasieff, who had worked extensively with Carey throughout the first half of her career.<ref name=\"shapiro5\"/> Aside from their growing creative differences, Mottola had given Afanasieff more opportunities to work with other artists.<ref name=\"shapiro6\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=122}}</ref> She felt Mottola was trying to separate her from Afanasieff, in hopes of keeping their relationship permanently strained.<ref name=\"shapiro6\"/> Due to the pressure and the awkward relationship Carey had now developed with Sony, she completed the album in a period of three months in the summer of 1999, quicker than any of her other albums.<ref name=\"shapiro6\"/> In an interview with ''Blitz TV'', Carey spoke of her decision to record the album in Capri:\n<blockquote>\nI love New York. But if I'm there, I want to go out, friends come to the studio, the phone rings constantly. But in Capri, I am in a remote place, and there is no one I can run into. I felt that in Capri I would be able to effectively finish the album on a shorter schedule. And I did. I made it in three months, I was like 'Get me off this label!' I couldn't take it. The situation there [Sony] was becoming increasingly difficult.<ref name=\"shapiro5\"/>\n</blockquote>\nLike her previous releases, Carey co-wrote and co-produced the album's material, working with several hip hop and R&B producers such as [[Jay-Z]], [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Missy Elliott]], [[Jermaine Dupri]], and [[Brian Michael Cox]].<ref name=\"shapiro6\"/> For the album's debut single release, Carey collaborated with Jay-Z and DJ Clue.<ref name=\"bronson\">{{harvnb|Bronson|2003|p=888}}</ref> During the spring of 1999, Carey began working with Clue on several [[hook (music)|hooks]] and melodies for the lead single. After a few hours, they decided to include a hip hop star on the track, which eventually led to Jay-Z.<ref name=\"bronson\"/> Carey's longtime friend and back-up vocalist [[Trey Lorenz]], who was featured on her remake of the [[Jackson 5]] song \"[[I'll Be There (Jackson 5 song)#Mariah Carey version|I'll Be There]],\" added \"some soft male [back-up] vocals.\"<ref name=\"bronson\"/> Carey worked with Lewis and Jam on the ballad \"[[Thank God I Found You]].\"<ref name=\"bronson2\">{{harvnb|Bronson|2003|p=892}}</ref> She had already been in the studio with the duo several times when she contacted them to meet her at the studio, where she told them that she had come up with the title, hook, and melody. Usually, when Carey was writing the songs for ''Rainbow'', James \"Big Jim\" Wright would play the organ or piano and assist Carey to find the \"right melody.\"<ref name=\"bronson2\"/> However, since Wright was not present, Lewis played the organ while Carey directed him with her [[vocal range|lower registers]], providing the [[chord progression]]. They composed the song and recorded Carey's vocals. Knowing she wanted to introduce a male vocalist on the track, Lewis brought R&B singer [[Joe (singer)|Joe]] and pop group [[98 Degrees]] into the studio.<ref name=\"bronson2\"/> After a few hours, the group and Joe had recorded all their vocals and the song was complete.<ref name=\"bronson2\"/> In an interview with Bronson, Lewis discussed the night Carey wrote \"Thank God I Found You:\"\n<blockquote>\nIt all happened that night. She told us the title of the song, the concept and sang us the melody. We usually have Big Jim Wright sit in on those kind of sessions to work out the chords. he wasn't there so I had to work on the chord myself. So I was playing and there was a part where I said 'Man, what chord am I supposed to do here?' and Mariah has such a good ear that she sang me the chord.<ref name=\"bronson2\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\nWhile the album was immersed further into mainstream R&B territory, Carey included some of her classic ballads and tender love songs on the album, working with writers and producers such as [[David Foster]] and [[Diane Warren]].<ref name=\"shapiro6\"/> The idea to work with Warren was suggested by Foster, who thought that the two would be able to \"hammer out one hell of a ballad\" together.<ref name=\"shapiro6\"/> The two wrote and produced the song titled \"After Tonight.\" Carey felt the song was a perfect metaphor for her relationship with Miguel, describing their romance in Capri. While the song was deemed a success by both parties, they described their working relationship with mixed feelings.<ref name=\"shapiro6\"/> According to Foster, who was involved in the writing session, Carey and Warren would not always agree on the lyrics and melodious structure of the song. He described it as a \"give and take relationship\"; Warren would offer lyrics and Carey would not like them; she wanted something more intricate and detailed. Carey would produce a hook or lyrics that Warren did not feel were a perfect fit.<ref name=\"shapiro6\"/> In the end, Foster felt that they worked \"well together.\" After recording the song, Carey invited Miguel to record the song with her as a duet.<ref name=\"shapiro7\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=123}}</ref> However, after recording his verses several times, Foster and Carey realized that the song would not turn out the way they planned.<ref name=\"shapiro7\"/> Foster said the song's key was \"too high for him\"; the voices did not harmonize well. Carey did not have time to re-record her vocals in a lower key to accommodate Miguel's verses.<ref name=\"shapiro7\"/> Miguel, furious over the failed collaboration, later sent a cut-up tape of the demo to Foster. Carey, Warren, and Foster also wrote \"[[Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)]],\" one of the other ballads featured on ''Rainbow''.<ref name=\"shapiro7\"/>\n\n==Music and lyrics==\n{{Quote box|width=30%|align=right|style=padding:8px|quote=\"It was from the standpoint of girls who keep going back to the same guy and they can't help themselves. They know they're going to get hurt. I've been one of those girls, so I know there's a lot of them out there.\"|source=\u2014Carey, describing the lyrics of \"Heartbreaker\"\n }}\nAs with ''Butterfly'', songs for ''Rainbow'' were chosen to solidify Carey's reputation as a multi-genre artist.<ref name=\"bronson\"/> Throughout the first phase of her career, Carey's albums predominantly consisted of pop and adult contemporary ballads. ''Rainbow'' mixed hip hop and R&B-flavored upbeat songs with softer and lyrically intense ballads resembling those that Carey had previously recorded.<ref name=\"bronson\"/> \"[[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]],\" Carey's first collaboration with Jay-Z, used a sample from \"Attack of the Name Game,\" recorded by [[Stacy Lattisaw]], as its hook. The loop originated from \"The Name Game\" by [[Shirley Ellis]];<ref name=\"bronson\"/> Ellis and co-writer [[Lincoln Chase]] are credited as songwriters on the track. Carey incorporated the hook into the song's melody, and added instrumentation.<ref name=\"bronson\"/> Lyrically, the song chronicles the heartbreak the protagonist feels after learning of her lover's infidelity. \"[[Thank God I Found You]]\" features vocals from Joe and 98 Degrees, as well as songwriting and production from Carey and Lewis.<ref name=\"bronson2\"/> According to Carey, the song reflects on events in her own life at the time, with the lyrics describing the completion the protagonist feels after \"finding\" their lover. Joe provides the main male vocal throughout each verse, and 98 Degrees sing the background vocals and the [[Bridge (music)|bridge]].<ref name=\"bronson2\"/>\n\nPrior to the album's recording, Mariah and her sister, Alison Carey had a falling out in their relationship.<ref name=\"shapiro8\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=126\u2013127}}</ref> Alison had contracted [[AIDS]] in 1988, when she was 27, and in 1994 she blamed Mariah for many of her problems and heartbreaks throughout the years. Her children were taken away while she received treatment for AIDS and for mental health issues.<ref name=\"shapiro8\"/> Carey wrote a song titled \"Petals,\" which she describes as the most honest lyrics she has ever written. The song tells of Carey's feelings for her sister, while illustrating the pain Allison's betrayal and suffering have caused.<ref name=\"shapiro8\"/> In an interview with Bronson, Carey described the meaning of the lyrics of \"Petals\":\n<blockquote>\nIt is a great outlet for me to go into the studio and write a song like 'Petals', which is one of my most personal songs and remains one of my favorites. I think [it had the most] honest lyrics I've ever written. The song chronicles a lot of past emotions I've felt to certain people close to me, and the way I feel towards them and how their actions have impacted me personally. For that reason, I sang in my lower registers, trying to add that breathy effect to go hand in hand with the song's composition.<ref name=\"bronson\"/>\n</blockquote>\n\"After Tonight\" was a song Carey wrote with David Foster and Diane Warren. Carey had strong feelings about the song, as she wrote it about her relationship with Luis Miguel.<ref name=\"shapiro11\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=135\u2013136}}</ref> The song was compared instrumentally to \"[[My All]]\" from ''Butterfly'', which features traces of Latin and guitar instrumentation.<ref name=\"shapiro11\"/> In the lyrics, the protagonist asks her lover if he will still love her and come back to her \"after tonight.\" Carey's cover of the [[Phil Collins]] song \"[[Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)]]\" was originally intended to be a solo ballad. The song was re-done after the album was released, with music by the Irish band [[Westlife]] replacing the song's instrumental bridge.<ref name=\"shapiro11\"/> \"[[Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)]]\" was one of the album's most uplifting ballads, lyrically serving as an anthem for fans and listeners. The message, Carey said, was a personal theme of hers growing up, of not letting others \"bring her down\" and not allowing them to take away the light inside her.<ref name=\"shapiro11\"/>\n\"How Much\" is a duet with [[Usher (singer)|Usher]] and features a sample from [[Tupac Shakur]]'s \"Me and My Girlfriend.\"\n\n==Conflict with Sony==\nAs with ''Butterfly'' two years earlier, ''Rainbow'' became the center of conflict between Carey and her label.<ref name=\"shapiro10\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=133\u2013134}}</ref> After her divorce from Sony record official and Columbia CEO Tommy Mottola, Carey's working relationship with the label deteriorated. She intended for \"Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)\" to be the third single from ''Rainbow'', as it held very personal lyrical content. However, Sony made it clear that they intended the third single should be a more upbeat and urban track.<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/> The difference in opinion led to a very public feud, as Carey began posting messages on her webpage in early and mid-2000, telling fans inside information on the dispute, as well as instructing them to request \"Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)\" on radio stations.<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/> One of the messages Carey left on her page read:\n<blockquote>\nBasically, a lot of you know the political situation in my professional career is not positive. It's been really, really hard. I don't even know if this message is going to get to you because I don't know if they want you to hear this. I'm getting a lot of negative feedback from certain corporate people. But I am not willing to give up.<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/>\n</blockquote>\nCarey's actions were given mixed reception, with critics and executives commending her bold actions regarding a song she felt needed to be heard, while others criticized her for publicizing the dispute further.<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/> Soon after, Sony stripped Carey's webpage of messages and began negotiations. Fearing to lose their label's highest seller and the best-selling artist of the decade, Sony chose to release the song.<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/> Carey, initially content with the agreement, soon found out that the song had only been given a very limited and low-promotion release, which meant the song failed to chart on the official US chart, and made international charting extremely difficult and unlikely.<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/>\n\n==Promotion==\n{{Main article|Rainbow World Tour}}\nPrior to the album's release, Carey made an appearance on ''[[Pavarotti & Friends for Guatemala and Kosovo]]'', performing \"My All\" and \"[[Hero (Mariah Carey song)|Hero]]\" alongside [[Luciano Pavarotti]] in a live duet.<ref name=\"shapiro9\"/> The concert benefit was filmed live in [[Modena]], Italy, during the summer of 1999 and was released for sale on September 21, with funds being donated to relief efforts for natural disasters in [[Guatemala]] and [[Kosovo]].<ref name=\"shapiro9\"/> Carey made several live television and award show appearances at this time, and recorded her own [[Fox Broadcasting Company]] special,<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/> titled ''The Mariah Carey Homecoming Special''. A mini-concert filmed at Carey's old high school in Huntington, New York, the special aired on Fox on December 21, 1999.<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/> Carey performed \"Heartbreaker\" and its accompanying remix at the [[1999 MTV Europe Music Awards|MTV European Music Awards]], held on November 11, 1999, in [[Dublin]], Ireland. Additionally, the song was performed on ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', the British music chart program ''[[Top of the Pops]]'', and ''[[Today (NBC program)|The Today Show]]'', which included a performance of \"Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)\" and \"Hero.\"<ref name=\"shapiro11\"/> \"Thank God I Found You was performed live at the 2000 [[American Music Awards of 2000|American Music Awards]] as well as on several European programs, including ''Top of the Pops'' and ''[[Ian Wright|Friday Night's All Wright]]'' in the United Kingdom, [[NRJ Radio|NRJ]] and ''[[European Golden Shoe|Soulier d'Or]]'' in France, ''[[Wetten, dass..?]]'' in Germany, and ''[[Quelli che... il Calcio]]'' in Italy.<ref name=\"shapiro11\"/> The album's final two releases, \"Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)\" and \"Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now),\" were performed on ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'' and at the 2000 [[Blockbuster Inc.|Blockbuster Entertainment Awards]].<ref name=\"shapiro10\"/>\n\nIn order to promote ''Rainbow'', Carey embarked of her fourth headlining and third worldwide tour. Titled the [[Rainbow World Tour]], it included nineteen shows: six in Europe, four in Asia, eight in the United States, and one in Canada.<ref name=\"shapiro9\">{{harvnb|Shapiro|2001|pp=129\u2013130}}</ref> For Carey's previous two tours, she had only visited Europe and Asia, due to the mixed reception of her [[Music Box Tour|debut stateside tour]] in 1993.<ref name=\"shapiro9\"/> However, after achieving record-breaking ticket sales throughout Asia and instant sellouts in Europe, Carey felt secure enough to once again tour her native country. The [[set list]] featured songs from most of Carey's previous studio albums, as well as some tracks from ''Rainbow''.<ref name=\"shapiro9\"/> [[Missy Elliott]] and [[Da Brat]] served as opening acts for the US leg of the tour. Ticket sales were very strong; the entire US leg sold out in a matter of days. The Asian and European leg mirrored the commercial success of her previous two tours.<ref name=\"shapiro9\"/> Reviews for the tour varied from positive to mixed. Some critics and fans reproached her of having a \"tired and hoarse voice,\" while others commented on Carey's choice of wardrobe. Several critics and many concert-goers praised the tour, calling it an intense celebration of Carey's career.<ref name=\"shapiro9\"/>\n\n===Singles===\n[[File:Mariah Carey Charmbracelet London.jpg|thumb|left|Carey performing the lead single \"[[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]]\" live on her [[Charmbracelet World Tour]] in 2003.]]\nFive singles were released from ''Rainbow''; two were worldwide international releases and three were limited promotional releases. \"Heartbreaker,\" the album's first worldwide release, became Carey's fourteenth chart topper in the United States.<ref name=\"Billboard Hot 100\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=mariah carey|chart=Hot 100}}|title=Mariah Carey Album & Song Chart History: Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 14, 2010}}</ref> Aside from staying atop the US chart for two weeks, the song reached the chart's summit in Canada and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Canadian Hot 100\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=mariah carey|chart=Billboard Canadian Hot 100}}|title=Canadian Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref> Elsewhere, \"Heartbreaker\" achieved high charting, peaking within the top five in France and the United Kingdom, and within the top ten in Australia, Belgium, the Netherlands, Germany, and Switzerland.<ref name=nz>{{cite web|url=https://charts.nz/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Mariah+Carey|title=New Zealand Charts - Mariah Carey|work=charts.nz|publisher= Hung Medien|accessdate=January 21, 2010}}</ref><ref name=ger>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/Carey%2CMariah?sort=entry&type=longplay|title=Chartverfolgung / Carey, Mariah / Longplay|language=German|publisher=musicline.de PhonoNet|accessdate=April 7, 2010}}</ref> The song received mixed reviews from critics. Arion Berger from ''Rolling Stone'' called the song Carey's \"most insinuating: nasal, silken, declarative, riding the percolating beat.\"<ref name=rs/> However, while dismissing some of the song's vocals and the incorporation of the hook, he complimented its marriage of pop and hip hop through Jay-Z's verses.<ref name=rs/> The song's music video became one of the most expensive music videos of all time, costing an estimated $2.5 million.<ref name=\"bronson\"/> The video features Carey visiting a movie theater with her friends, where she finds her lover with another woman. \"Thank God I Found You\" was released as the second worldwide single from the album. While becoming Carey's fifteenth chart topper in the US, the song achieved moderate chart success in Europe and other territories. Berger called it a \"gospel soar\" and complimented Carey's vocals, as well as the harmonies by 98 Degrees.<ref name=rs/> The music video features footage from a live concert with Carey and the band performing the song.\n\n\"[[Crybaby (Mariah Carey song)|Crybaby]]\" and \"Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)\" were released simultaneously as a [[A-side and B-side|double A-side]], with very limited promotion from Sony.<ref name=\"shapiro8\"/> These two songs, especially the latter, became the center of a very public controversy between Carey and her label, due to their alleged low promotion of the album.<ref name=\"shapiro8\"/> Carey and Snoop Dogg were featured in the music video for \"Crybaby,\" with Carey playing an anxious woman who can't sleep at night due to her lover's infidelity. A music video for \"Can't Take That Away\" was released around the same time, which features Carey on a rooftop garden. Carey sings during a rain storm, and towards the video's conclusion, the sun arises, bring forth a \"new day.\" The final single from ''Rainbow'', \"Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now),\" was given a limited release as well. After performing moderately around the world, a new version of the song, featuring [[Westlife]], was released in Ireland and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"shapiro11\"/> It became successful there, peaking at number one in both territories, and became Carey's second UK chart topper.<ref name=\"shapiro11\"/> The song's video features Carey and Westlife on a boat in Capri. Scenes of the group exploring the island are cut with scenes of them in the studio, though Carey never re-recorded her vocals from the original version.<ref name=\"shapiro11\"/>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=allmusic/>\n| rev2 = ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Considine|first=J. D.|authorlink=J. D. Considine|date=November 2, 1999|url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/1999-11-02/features/9911020253_1_mariah-carey-heartbreaker-carey-offers|title=`Rainbow' paints emotional arc|work=[[The Baltimore Sun]]|accessdate=September 17, 2016}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating-Christgau|hm2}}<ref name=\"CG\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2000|pages=xvi, 50|title=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan]]|isbn=0312245602|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/christgausconsum00chri_0}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|year=2011|chapter=Mariah Carey|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|isbn=0857125958|edition=5th}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev5Score = B+<ref name=ew/>\n| rev6 = ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|3.5|4}}<ref name=la/>\n| rev7 = ''[[MTV Networks Asia Pacific|MTV Asia]]''\n| rev7Score = 7/10<ref name=mtvasia>{{cite web|url=http://web.mtvasia.com/Review/CD/C1999000115.html|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Rainbow|author=Dara Cook|website=[[MTV Networks Asia Pacific]]|date=October 31, 1999|access-date=March 1, 2019|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Gdl9CqIx?url=http://web.mtvasia.com/Review/CD/C1999000115.html|archive-date=May 15, 2013|quote=\"Rainbow\" is perfect, and why wouldn't it be? It is Mariah. It is pop, it is R&B, even sometimes hip-hop}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=rs/>\n| rev9 = ''[[USA Today]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3|4}}<ref name=usa/>\n}}\n''Rainbow'' received positive reviews from critics, many of whom noted the new direction in Carey's music.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shapiro|first=Marc|page=125|quote=''Rainbow'' raced up the album charts to number two amid a tidal wave of solid reviews that emphasized Mariah's new musical direction.|title=Mariah Carey|publisher=[[ECW Press]]|isbn=1550224441}}</ref> In ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', [[Danyel Smith]] wrote that \"what began on ''Butterfly'' as a departure ends up on ''Rainbow'' a progression \u2013 perhaps the first compelling proof of Carey's true colors as an artist.\"<ref name=ew>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,271534,00.html|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Rainbow|last=Smith|first=Danyel|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]. [[Time Warner]]|date=November 12, 1999|accessdate=March 8, 2011}}</ref> Arion Berger from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' viewed it as a genuine R&B and hip hop album, a \"sterling chronicle of the state of accessible hip-hop balladeering at the close of 1999.\" Aside from calling some of the ballads \"banal,\" Berger concluded his review that \"''Rainbow'' is at its best\u2014and Carey at her most comfortable\u2014when urbane hip-hop stylings and faux R&B coexist in smooth middle-of-the-road harmony.\"<ref name=rs>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/rainbow-19991125|title=Mariah Carey Rainbow|last=Berger|first=Arion|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]. [[Limited liability company]]|date=November 25, 1999|accessdate=March 6, 2011|quote=Rainbow is at its best \u2014 and Carey at her most comfortable \u2014 when urbane hip-hop stylings and faux R&B coexist in smooth middle-of-the-road harmony}}</ref> Elysa Gardner from the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote in her review: \"Exhibiting an emotional authority to match her technical prowess, Carey gives us a vision of love that's dynamic without being ostentatious.\"<ref name=la>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/oct/31/entertainment/ca-28099|title=Record Rack|last=Gardner|first=Elysa|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=October 31, 1999|accessdate=March 10, 2011}}</ref> Steve Jones from ''[[USA Today]]'' deemed the record \"colorful\" and \"some of her most compelling work.\"<ref name=usa>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/lmds784.htm#review|title=A Prism Of Pure Carey And A Bit Of The Bubbly|last=Jones|first=Steve|work=[[USA Today]]|date=December 12, 1999|url-status=dead|accessdate=March 6, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020052259/http://www.usatoday.com/life/music/lmds784.htm#review|archivedate=October 20, 2008|quote=On her ninth album, Rainbow (3 stars out of four), Carey has her feet firmly in both the hip-hop and the pop/ adult-contemporary markets}}</ref> ''[[Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]] gave the album a two-star honorable mention, indicating a \"likable effort consumers attuned to its overriding aesthetic or individual vision may well enjoy.\" He cited \"Heartbreaker\" and \"Crybaby\" as highlights while writing that Carey was \"not a 'real' r&b [[wikt:thrush#Noun|thrush]], but good enough to fake it.\"<ref name=\"CG\"/>\n\nAmy Linden from ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]'' was less impressed by the album, particularly the songs on which Carey sings over hip hop samples or alongside guest rappers, deeming it a commonplace formula--\"pairing a singing thrush with a rhyming thug.\"<ref name=vibe>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YCgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA260-IA6&dq=mariah+carey+rainbow&hl=en&ei=qyduTabsD8G4tgfdvezwDg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=5&ved=0CEQQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=mariah%20carey%20rainbow&f=false|title=Mariah Carey 'Rainbow'|last=Linden|first=Amy|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|date=December 12, 1999|accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref> [[Stephen Thomas Erlewine]] from [[AllMusic]] said it was \"the first Carey album where she's written personal lyrics, and allusions to her separation from Mottola.\" He called the lyrics \"true\" and \"deep,\" but found the songs \"ballad-heavy\" and \"repetitious,\" adding that the album followed the formula of Carey's previous records too precisely. In his opinion, \"it would have been a more effective album if the heartbreak, sorrow, and joy that bubbles underneath the music were brought to the surface.\"<ref name=allmusic>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=rainbow-r443455|pure_url=yes}}|title=Rainbow \u2013 Mariah Carey|last=Erlewine Thomas|first=Stephen|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n[[File:Mariah Carey Mimi Tour 1.jpg|thumb|right|Carey performing the single \"[[Thank God I Found You]]\" during her [[Adventures of Mimi Tour]] in 2006.]]\n''Rainbow'' debuted at number two on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart with 323,000 units sold, the highest first-week sales of Carey's career at that time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_BQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=RA1-PA47&dq=rainbow+323,000&hl=en&ei=AAl0TanBGJKw0QHvk-DEAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=rainbow%20323%2C000&f=false|title=Carey Starts New Day; Charts Move Into New Home|last=Mayfeild|first=Geoff|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=April 30, 2005|accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref> In its second week, the album stayed at number two, selling an additional 228,000 copies, barred from the top by [[Faith Hill]]'s ''[[Breathe (Faith Hill album)|Breathe]]''.<ref name=\"shapiro3\"/> In its eighth week, ''Rainbow'' experienced its highest weekly sales\u2014during the Christmas week of 1999\u2014selling 369,000 copies, while placing at number nine.<ref name=\"shapiro3\"/> It became Carey's first studio album since ''[[Merry Christmas (Mariah Carey album)|Merry Christmas]]'' (1994) to not reach the top position in the United States. In total, ''Rainbow'' stayed in the top twenty for ten weeks and on the chart for thirty-five, making one re-entry.<ref name=\"shapiro3\"/> It was certified triple-[[RIAA certification|Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA), denoting shipments of three million copies throughout the United States.<ref name=\"Mariah Carey's Rainbow's USA certifications\">{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=1&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=Rainbow&artist=Mariah%20Carey&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=Artist&perPage=25|title=Gold & Platinum Search Results: Rainbow|publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]]|accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> According to [[Nielsen SoundScan]], the album's sales in the US are estimated at 2,968,000 copies.<ref name=askbillboard>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/267631/ask-billboard-madonna-vs-whitney-vs-mariah|title=Ask Billboard: Madonna vs. Whitney ...vs. Mariah|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=August 21, 2009|work=Billboard|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media]]|accessdate=April 7, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ussales\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1555095/ask-billboard-belindas-back-jt-too-mariah-careys-album-sales|title=Ask Billboard: Belinda's Back, JT Too, Mariah Carey's Album Sales & More|last=Trust|first=Gary|date=April 2, 2013|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 11, 2013}}</ref> In Canada, ''Rainbow'' debuted at number two on the [[Canadian Albums Chart]], and was certified triple-[[List of music recording certifications|Platinum]] by the [[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] (CRIA).<ref name=\"Canada's Certification-databases\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |title=CRIA: Certification-database |publisher=[[Canadian Recording Industry Association]] |accessdate=August 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331121149/http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php |archivedate=March 31, 2010 }}</ref> Sales in Canada are estimated at 300,000 units.<ref name=\"canada sales\">{{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/C/Carey_Mariah/2000/02/10/743780.html |title=Carey's T.O. concert tix |last=Stevenson |first=Jane |work=[[Jam!]] |publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|CANOE]] |accessdate=August 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20150402100117/http://jam.canoe.ca/Music/Artists/C/Carey_Mariah/2000/02/10/743780.html |archivedate=April 2, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n''Rainbow'' debuted at number three on the [[ARIA Charts|Australian Albums Chart]], staying within the chart for seven weeks. The album was Platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] (ARIA), denoting shipments of 70,000 copies.<ref name=\"Australian Certifications 1999\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/aria-charts-accreditations-albums-1999.htm|title=ARIA Charts \u2013 Accreditations \u2013 1999 Albums|work=[[ARIA Charts]]|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> In France, the album experienced strong success, debuting atop the albums chart and remaining inside the top forty for thirty-four weeks. The album was certified triple-Platinum by the [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] (SNEP), with estimated sales of 900,000 copies.<ref name=\"French Platinum certifications 2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/page-259165.xml?year=2000&type=12 |title=Certifications Albums Platine \u2013 ann\u00e9e 2000 |work=Disque Queen France |publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]] |language=French |accessdate=August 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419212756/http://www.disqueenfrance.com/fr/page-259165.xml?year=2000&type=12 |archivedate=April 19, 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.infodisc.fr/CDCertif_P.php?debut=100|title=Les Albums Certifications \u2013 Platine|work=InfoDisc|publisher=Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|language=French|accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> In Germany, ''Rainbow'' peaked at number three, and received a Platinum certification from the [[Bundesverband Musikindustrie]] (BVMI), denoting shipments of 500,000 units.<ref name=\"German certifications database\">{{cite certification|region=Germany|accessdate=August 23, 2010|title=Rainbow}}</ref>  in the United Kingdom Rainbow debuted at number eight and stayed within the top 100 for 20 weeks.<ref name=uk>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/3/1999-11-13/|title=Top 40 Official UK Albums Chart|work=[[UK Albums Chart]]|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|date=November 13, 1999|accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref> ''Rainbow'' was certified Platinum by the [[British Phonographic Industry]] (BPI), denoting shipments of 300,000 units.<ref name=\"BPI certification-database\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=Certified Awards Search |publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |accessdate=August 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr0Evm3j?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |archivedate=January 17, 2010 }}</ref> Additionally, ''Rainbow'' received Platinum certification in Brazil, with 250,000 copies,<ref name=\"Brazil's Certification-database\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abpd.org.br/certificados.asp |title=Certificados: Estou buscando por |publisher=[[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Brasileira dos Produtores de Discos]] |language=Portuguese |accessdate=August 23, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906003856/http://www.abpd.org.br/certificados.asp |archivedate=September 6, 2010 }}</ref> Platinum in New Zealand,<ref name=\"scapolo\">{{Cite book| author=Scapolo, Dean| title=The Complete New Zealand Music Charts 1966\u20132006 | publisher=RIANZ| year=2007 | isbn=978-1-877443-00-8}}</ref> triple-Platinum in Spain,<ref name=\"spain\">{{cite book |last=Salaverri|first=Fernando|title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002|edition=1st |date=September 2005|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Autor-SGAE|location=Spain|isbn=84-8048-639-2}}</ref> Platinum in Argentina,<ref name=\"Argentina's Gold/Platinum Certifications for Mariah Carey\">{{cite web|url=http://www.capif.org.ar/Default.asp?PerDesde_MM=0&PerDesde_AA=0&PerHasta_MM=0&PerHasta_AA=0&interprete=mariah+carey&album=&LanDesde_MM=0&LanDesde_AA=0&LanHasta_MM=0&LanHasta_AA=0&Galardon=O&Tipo=0&ACCION2=+Search+&ACCION=Buscar&CO=5&CODOP=ESOP|title=Discos de Oro y Platino|language=Spanish|publisher=[[Argentine Chamber of Phonograms and Videograms Producers]]|accessdate=October 7, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20110706085111/http://www.capif.org.ar/Default.asp?PerDesde_MM=0&PerDesde_AA=0&PerHasta_MM=0&PerHasta_AA=0&interprete=mariah+carey&album=&LanDesde_MM=0&LanDesde_AA=0&LanHasta_MM=0&LanHasta_AA=0&Galardon=O&Tipo=0&ACCION2=+Search+&ACCION=Buscar&CO=5&CODOP=ESOP|archivedate=July 6, 2011}}</ref> Gold in Belgium,<ref name=\"Belgium's certifications 1999\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ultratop.be/xls/Awards%201999.htm|title= Ultratop 50 Albums Vlaanderen 1999|publisher=[[Ultratop]]|accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> Platinum in the Netherlands,<ref name=\"Dutch Certification to Ranibow\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nvpi.nl/|title=Mariah Carey \u2013 Rainbow|publisher=[[Nederlandse Vereniging van Producenten en Importeurs van beeld- en geluidsdragers]]|accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> and Gold in Switzerland.<ref name=\"Swiss Certifications 1999\">{{cite web |url=http://www.swisscharts.com/awards.asp?year=1999|title=Awards 1999|work=[[Swiss Music Charts]]|publisher=[[International Federation of the Phonographic Industry]]|accessdate=August 23, 2010}}</ref> The album has sold an estimated eight million copies worldwide.<ref name=\"globalsales\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| title1 = [[Heartbreaker (Mariah Carey song)|Heartbreaker]]\n| note1= Featuring [[Jay-Z]]\n| writer1= {{hlist|[[Mariah Carey]]|[[Jay-Z|Shawn Carter]]|Shirley Elliston|Lincoln Chase|Michael Walden|Jeffrey Cohen}}\n| extra1= {{hlist|Carey|[[DJ Clue]]}}\n| length1= 4:46\n| title2 = [[Can't Take That Away (Mariah's Theme)]]\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Carey|[[Diane Warren]]}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Carey|[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]]}}\n| length2 = 4:33\n| title3 = Bliss\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Carey|[[James Harris III]]|[[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Terry Lewis]]|James \"Big Jim\" Wright}}\n| extra3 = {{hlist|Carey|Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis}}\n| length3 = 5:44\n| title4 = How Much\n| note4 = Featuring [[Usher (singer)|Usher]] & [[Jermaine Dupri]]\n| writer4 = {{hlist|Carey|[[Bryan-Michael Cox]]|[[Jermaine Dupri]]|[[Tupac Shakur]]|Tyrone Wrice|Ricky Rouse}}\n| extra4 = {{hlist|Carey|Cox|Dupri}}\n| length4 = 3:31\n| title5 = After Tonight\n| writer5 = {{hlist|Carey|Warren|[[David Foster]]}}\n| extra5 = {{hlist|Carey|Foster}}\n| length5 = 4:16\n| title6 = X-Girlfriend\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Carey|[[Kandi Burruss]]|[[Kevin \"She'kspere\" Briggs]]}}\n| extra6 = {{hlist|Carey|She'kspere}}\n| length6 = 3:58\n| title7 = Heartbreaker\n| note7 = Remix) (Featuring [[Da Brat]], [[Missy Elliott]] & [[DJ Clue?]]\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Carey|[[Shawntae Harris]]|[[Missy Elliott|Melissa Elliott]]|Ricardo Emanuel Brown|[[Warren G|Warren Griffin III]]|[[Dr. Dre|Andre Young]]|Nathaniel Hale}}\n| extra7 = {{hlist|Carey|DJ Clue}}\n| length7 = 4:32\n| title8 = Vulnerability (Interlude)\n| writer8 = Carey\n| extra8 = Carey\n| length8= 1:12\n| title9 = [[Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)#Mariah Carey version|Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)]]\n| writer9 = [[Phil Collins]]\n| extra9 = {{hlist|Carey|Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis}}\n| length9 = 3:25\n| title10 = [[Crybaby (Mariah Carey song)|Crybaby]]\n| note10 = Featuring [[Snoop Dogg]]\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Carey|Howie Hersh|[[Snoop Doggy Dogg]]|Trey Lorenz|Timothy Gatlin|Gene Griffin|Aaron Hall III|Teddy Riley}}\n| extra10 = {{hlist|Carey|[[Damizza]]}}\n| length10 = 5:20\n| title11 = Did I Do That?\n| note11 = Featuring [[Mystikal]] & [[Master P]]\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Carey|Craig Bazile|Joseph Johnson|Tracey Waples|Joseph Smokey Robinson|Wardell Joseph Quezergue}}\n| extra11 = {{hlist|Carey|Waples}}\n| length11 = 4:16\n| title12 = Petals\n| writer12 = {{hlist|Carey|Harris|Lewis|Wright}}\n| extra12 = {{hlist|Carey|Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Big Jim}}\n| length12 = 4:23\n| title13 = Rainbow (Interlude)\n| writer13 = {{hlist|Carey|Harris|Lewis}}\n| extra13 = {{hlist|Carey|Lewis}}\n| length13 = 1:32\n| title14 = [[Thank God I Found You]]\n| note14 = Featuring [[Joe (singer)|Joe]] & [[98 Degrees]]\n| writer14 = {{hlist|Carey|Harris|Lewis}}\n| extra14 = {{hlist|Carey|Lewis}}\n| length14 = 4:17\n|}}\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = French hidden bonus track\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| title15 = Theme from ''Mahogany'' (Do You Know Where You're Going To)\n| writer15 = {{hlist|[[Michael Masser]]|[[Gerry Goffin|Gerald Goffin]]}}\n| extra15 = {{hlist|Carey|[[Stevie J.]]|Mike Mason}}\n| length15 = 3:47\n}}\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 2000 re-release edition bonus track<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goods.ruten.com.tw/item/show?21518220544026|title=\u9732\u5929\u62cd\u8ce3-\u53f0\u7063 NO.1 \u62cd\u8ce3\u7db2\u7ad9|work=ruten.com.tw|accessdate=March 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190104124614/https://goods.ruten.com.tw/item/show?21518220544026|archive-date=January 4, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length =\n| title15 = [[Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)#Mariah Carey and Westlife version|Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)]]\n| note15 = duet with [[Westlife]]\n| writer15 = Phil Collins\n| extra15 = {{hlist|Carey|[[Steve Mac]]}}\n| length15 = 3:25\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n* \"Heartbreaker\" contains a sample of \"Attack of the Name Game\" by [[Stacy Lattisaw]].\n* \"How Much\" contains a sample of \"[[The Don Killuminati: The 7 Day Theory|Me and My Girlfriend]]\" by [[Makaveli]].\n* \"Heartbreaker (Remix)\" contains a sample of \"Ain't No Fun (If the Homies Can't Have None)\" by [[Snoop Dogg]].\n* \"Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)\" is a cover of \"[[Against All Odds (Take a Look at Me Now)]]\" by [[Phil Collins]].\n* \"Crybaby\" contains samples of \"Piece of My Love\" by [[Guy (band)|Guy]] and \"[[Georgy Porgy (song)|Georgy Porgy]]\" by [[Toto (band)|Toto]].\n* \"Did I Do That?\" contains a sample of \"It Ain't My Fault 2\" by [[Silkk the Shocker]].\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n'''Personnel'''<ref name=\"Booklet\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Rainbow (Liner Notes)|others=Mariah Carey |year=1999 |first=Mariah |last=Carey |authorlink=Mariah Carey |type=Compact Disc |publisher=Columbia Records |location=New York City, New York }}</ref>\n* [[Mariah Carey]] \u2013 lead vocals, songwriting, background vocals\n* [[David Foster]] \u2013 keyboard, songwriting\n* [[Diane Warren]] \u2013 songwriting\n* [[Narada Michael Walden]] \u2013 guitars, programming\n* [[Bryan-Michael Cox]] \u2013 bass, keyboards\n* [[Jermaine Dupri]] \u2013 programming, percussion\n* James \"Big Jim\" Wright \u2013 keyboard, bass\n* [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis|Terry Lewis]] \u2013 synthesizers, keyboards, rhythm programming\n* [[James Harris III]] \u2013 synthesizers\n* [[Trey Lorenz]] \u2013 background vocals\n* Cindy Mizelle \u2013 background vocals\n* Melonie Daniels \u2013 background vocals\n* [[Kelly Price]] \u2013 background vocals\n* Shanrae Price \u2013 background vocals\n{{col-2}}\n'''Production'''<ref name=\"Booklet\"/>\n* Mariah Carey \u2013 arranger, producer\n* David Foster \u2013 arranger, producer\n* Diane Warren \u2013 arranger\n* Jermaine Dupri \u2013 arranger, producer\n* Narada Michael Walden \u2013 producer\n* Terry Lewis \u2013 arranger, producer\n* James Harris \u2013 producer\n* Bryan-Michael Cox \u2013 producer\n* [[Missy Elliott|Melissa Elliott]] \u2013 producer\n* [[Snoop Dogg|Calvin Broadus]] \u2013 producer\n* [[Jay-Z|Shawn Carter]] \u2013 producer\n* [[DJ Clue]] \u2013 arranger, producer\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\